MERGE (prog1:`Program`{`id`:'P1',`name`:'Arctic Investigations Program',`fullName`:'Arctic Investigations Program',`shortName`:'AIP',`purpose`:'The mission of the Arctic Investigations Program (AIP) is prevention of infectious diseases in peoples of the Arctic and Subarctic with special emphasis on diseases of high incidence and concern among Alaska Natives and American Indians. Priority activities include prevention of diseases caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae type b, Helicobacter pylori, methicillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus, and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), as well as control of viral hepatitis and botulism. AIP conducts infectious diseases surveillance, provides and evaluates prevention services, and conducts applied research in collaboration with other programs within CDC and with the Alaska State Division of Public Health, Alaska Native Tribal Health Consortium, Native Health Corporations, Indian Health Service, foreign ministries of health, industry, and universities. MERGE (prog3:`Program`{`id`:'P3',`name`:'BioSense Program',`fullName`:'BioSense Program',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'The BioSense Program was created by congressional mandate as part of the Public Health Security and Bioterrorism Preparedness and Response Act of 2002, and it was launched by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 2003. BioSense is a near real-time surveillance system that receives and processes electronic healthcare encounter data, including, chief complaints, final diagnosis codes, procedure codes, clinical laboratory, pharmacy prescription, and patient demographic data from participating public health jurisdictions’ non-federal hospital emergency departments and inpatient facilities in addition to all United States Department of Defense (DoD) and Veterans Affairs (VA) outpatient hospitals and clinics nationwide. The BioSense Program also receives pharmacy data from a private sector health information exchange firm and laboratory data from two national level private sector clinical laboratories. The BioSense Program is in the process of transitioning from the original BioSense application to the BioSense 2.0 application that has new governance, a new organizational structure, and a new process for data submission and management. The Association of State and Territorial Health Officials (ASTHO) has been funded through a cooperative agreement with CDC’s Division of Notifiable Disease and Healthcare Information (DNDHI) within the Public Health Surveillance and Informatics Program Office (PHSIPO) of the Office of Surveillance, Epidemiology, and Laboratory Services (OSELS) to facilitate the governance of BioSense 2.0, and through a contract with a vendor, ASTHO will offer access and use of BioSense 2.0 on a voluntary basis to state, local, and territorial health jurisdictions. Unlike the BioSense 1.0 application where participating organizations’ data were processed and stored at CDC in the CDC owned and operated Information Technology Services Office’s Mid-Tier Data Center on secure servers, all data submitted by users in BioSense 2.0 will reside in a cloud-enabled, web-based platform that sits in the secure, private Government Cloud and is in compliance with the Federal Information Security Management Act. The platform will provide users with an exclusive secure space as well as tools for posting, receiving, controlling, analyzing, and sharing their public health surveillance information with other public health jurisdictions, CDC, or other public health partners. The public health jurisdiction will retain ownership of any data it contributes to its exclusive secure space within BioSense 2.0.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/BioSense/',`operationalStatus`:'Partially Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2003',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'Boston Public Health Commission, county of Sacramento, Denver Health & Hopital Authority, H&H Corp-Marion county, New York/HRI, Tarrant county, TX',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers, Health Information Exchanges, Private Laboratories , Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Tribal Health Departments',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return prog3;

Although this effort is well underway, fulfilling CDC\'s vision of a safer world in the next millennium requires long-term commitment and sustained effort. MERGE (prog18:`Program`{`id`:'P18',`name`:'HIV Drug Resistance',`fullName`:'HIV Drug Resistance',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'Surveillance of transmitted HIV drug resistance (HIVDR) and HIVDR emerging during treatment and also of antiretroviral treatment (ART) program factors associated with the emergence/prevention of HIVDR during treatment. Countries form HIVDR working groups generally based at the Ministry of Health. There are five surveillance elements: 1. HIVDR Early Warning Indicators (EWI) -- all ART sites, or representative ART sites, are surveyed annually for factors associated with HIVDR emergence/prevention: A. ART prescribing practices; B. Percentage of patients lost to follow-up after one year following ART start C. Retention on first-line ART at one year; D. Percentage of ART patients picking up their drugs on-time; E. Percentage of ART patients keeping their appointments on time F. Percentage of months in which there are no ART drug stock-outs. Sample size is calculated based on numbers of ART patients at the site. Targets are recommended; countries may select more stringent targets. 2. Monitoring of HIVDR prevention and associated factors at sentinel ART sites: HIVDR working groups select three - 15 sentinel sites annually and do baseline genotypes and endpoint genotypes on patients starting ART, and abstract other information from medical records associated with HIVDR prevention. 3. HIVDR transmission surveys: These surveys are each focused in one geographic area of the country and use a binominal sequential sampling technique which classifies prevalence of transmitted drug resistance for each of the three ART drug classes used in resource-limited countries as above or below two thresholds: 5% and 15%. 4. Cross-sectional surveys: A representative cross-section of ART patients on first-line ART are surveyed for viral load, and if the viral load is detectable (=ART failure), the specimen is genotyped to evaluate the resistance pattern. 5. Pediatric surveillance of initial HIVDR in children < =18 months of age: Remnant dried blood spots used for pediatric HIV diagnosis are genotyped for children who are HIV-positive, prevention-of-mother to child transmission (PMTCT) information is collected (which regimens received by child and mother) to evaluate resistance patterns associated with PMTCT and also for those children whose PMTCT status is recorded as \"unknown\". Information is used for public health action to change ART program practices at site and national level. The program also includes HIVDR prevention elements (training), a database into which survey data can be entered, a lab training and accreditation system for surveillance genotyping.',`webResource`:'http://www.who.int/hiv/topics/drugresistance/en/index.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2005',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Schools / Universities',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Schools / Universities',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return prog18;

MERGE (prog26:`Program`{`id`:'P26',`name`:'Migrant Serum Bank',`fullName`:'Migrant Serum Bank',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'The Migrant Serum Bank (MSB), a serum repository, was established in 2002 to provide the opportunity to understand important public health problems, such as vaccine-preventable diseases, intestinal parasites and other emerging infectious diseases that might affect migrant populations. Over 500,000 immigrants and refugees, who resettle to the US annually, are required to undergo medical examinations that address a limited number of communicable diseases of public health importance. NEDSS helps connect the healthcare system to public health departments and those health departments to CDC by: providing leadership and resources to state and local health departments to adopt standards-based systems needed to support national disease surveillance strategy; enabling health agencies to use information technology more effectively by developing patient-centered systems that helps health departments identify issues such as co-morbidities (multiple disease or conditions) that occur in the same individual over time; The VSD project was established in 1990 to monitor immunization safety and address the gaps in scientific knowledge about rare and serious adverse events following immunization. The VSD project includes a large linked database that uses administrative data sources at each MCO. Each participating site gathers data on vaccination (vaccine type, date of vaccination, concurrent vaccinations), medical outcomes (outpatient visits, inpatient visits, urgent care visits), birth data, and census data. The VSD project allows for planned immunization safety studies as well as timely investigations of hypotheses that arise from review of medical literature, reports to the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS), changes in immunization schedules, or the introduction of new vaccines. The objectives of VSD are to conduct population based research on immunization safety questions; to evaluate immunization safety hypotheses that arise from medical literature, passive surveillance systems, adjustments to immunization schedules, and introduction of new vaccines; to guide national immunization policy decisions; and to partner with healthcare providers, public health officials, and others to ensure the public has the best available information regarding the risks and benefits of immunizations.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/vaccinesafety/Activities/VSD.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1991',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'Local Managed Care Organizations',`dataProviders-Manual`:'Healthcare Providers',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Healthcare Providers',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return prog39;

Surveillance is conducted for invasive bacterial diseases due to pathogens of public health importance. For each case of invasive disease in the study population, a case report with basic demographic information is completed and, in most cases, bacterial isolates from a normally sterile site from patients are sent for further laboratory characterization. ABCs data are used to determine the incidence and epidemiologic characteristics of invasive disease due to the pathogens under surveillance and to provide an infrastructure for further research, such as special studies aimed at identifying risk factors for disease, post-licensure evaluation of vaccine efficacy, and monitoring effectiveness of prevention policies.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/abcs/index.htm',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1995',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'State / Territorial Health Departments',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys3;

AMES provides tools to aid in finding the etiology, or cause, of the illness. In four provinces in China, an international collaboration supported by the Global Disease Detection (GDD) Initiative is leveraging existing public health surveillance and laboratory networks to detect acute meningitis-encephalitis syndrome, known as AMES. The network is the result of an international collaboration supported by the Global Disease Detection (GDD) Initiative. The joint China CDC-WHO-U.S. CDC protocol for GDD leverages aspects of both National Notifiable Disease Reporting System (NNDRS) and the NPSS to build laboratory-confirmed surveillance for AMES. CDC has also collaborated in establishment of AMES surveillance in India and Bangladesh. In all focus countries, this GDD collaboration strategically builds on existing systems to benefit from strengths and lessons learned. These efforts aim to improve public health through surveillance, immunization planning, and strengthening systems to identify novel and emerging pathogens. The AMES surveillance primarily focuses on Japanese encephalitis, bacterial meningitis - Haemophilus influenza b, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Neisseria meningitides. The public health objective of the ABLES program is objective OSH-7 in Healthy People 2020, which is to reduce the rate of adults (age 16 or older) who have blood lead levels of 10 micrograms per deciliter (mcg/dL) or greater.  The ABLES program aims to accomplish this objective by building state capacity to initiate or improve adult blood lead surveillance programs which can accurately measure trends in adult blood lead levels and which can effectively intervene to prevent lead over-exposures. For many states, the BRFSS is the only available source of timely, accurate data on health-related behaviors. BRFSS was established in 1984 by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). More than 350,000 adults are interviewed each year, making the BRFSS the largest telephone health survey in the world. CaliciNet went live March 16, 2009, connecting state and local public health laboratories across the United States; information gleaned from the network will provide a better understanding of noroviruses and help control their spread. Worldwide, noroviruses are the main cause of foodborne diarrheal disease, accounting for more cases of gastroenteritis than all bacterial causes combined. About 1 in 13 Americans becomes ill with norovirus gastroenteritis every year. CaliciNet also has the potential to help identify possible links between clusters of norovirus illness and common-source exposures. CaliciNet uses reverse transcription–polymerase chain reaction followed by DNA sequencing of partial regions of the norovirus genome. Once generated, these sequences are entered into an electronic sequence database at each state and local laboratory that then upload the sequences to the national CaliciNet database. With this real-time sequence information from the different public health laboratories at their fingertips, thanks to CaliciNet, scientists will be able to a) Link individual cases and clusters as part of larger outbreaks b) Quickly determine if a sudden increase in the number of outbreaks is caused by a norovirus strain with a new unique sequence.',`webResource`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2009',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Public Laboratories, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Public Laboratories, Local Health Departments',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys19;

Such information may include but not be limited to Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) and Investigational New Drug (IND) information, lot recalls, and other related information and materials. Countermeasure and Response Administration (CRA) - CRA is an emergency preparedness and response asset useful for any event involving tracking of vaccine administration, dispensing of pharmaceuticals and medical materiel, or implementation of social distancing measures. CRA supports analysis of safety, coverage, and effectiveness during an event which improves patient outcomes. CRA is a flexible all-hazards system that reduces the need for development of new applications each time there is a new event. Countermeasure Inventory Tracking (CIT) - CIT (a.k.a. the Countermeasure Supply Chain Dashboard) is a situational awareness tool used by DSNS to construct a nationwide inventory supply picture. The Dashboard consolidates project area inventory data reported through CRA with data from the commercial drug sector. This consolidated data forms a complete inventory supply picture which informs situational awareness during an event. These components are intended to cooperate and interoperate to improve communications and event response efficiency. MERGE (ssys47:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS47',`name`:'Fetal Alcohol Syndrome (FAS) Surveillance',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'FAS Surveillance',`purpose`:'Fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS) is a permanent, lifelong condition that causes physical and mental disabilities. Unlike most birth defects, where the causes are unknown, the etiology of FAS (prenatal exposure to alcohol) is known. FAS is 100% preventable if a woman does not drink alcohol during pregnancy. Despite increasing efforts to prevent alcohol exposed pregnancies, children continue to be born with disabilities resulting from prenatal alcohol exposure. Studies by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) indicate FAS rates ranging from 0.2 to 1.5 per 1,000 live births in different areas of the United States. Other studies have estimated the rate of FAS at 0.5 to 2.0 cases per 1,000 live births. The variation in rates of FAS is likely a reflection of variation in study populations, case definition, case ascertainment sources, and surveillance methodologies among studies. CDC has been funding state health departments to establish or enhance population-based surveillance of FAS since 1997. As a result of these efforts, a standardized, multiple-source surveillance methodology was developed and implemented by the funded states. Currently, CDC funds three FAS surveillance programs located in Arizona, Colorado, and New York. These programs are using the standardized, multiple source methodology to determine the prevalence of FAS within a geographically defined area.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/fasd/research-tracking.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1995',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys47;

HABISS is a unique surveillance system that includes not only human health data, but also animal health data and environmental data about the harmful algal blooms (HABs) themselves. Data collection is organized in modular format that can be expanded to suit the needs of state and local health and environmental protection agencies. In the future, data collected and stored in HABISS will be used to assist in predicting local HABs, thus allowing state public health and environmental health prevention activities to be in place not only in response to reports of human or animal illnesses, but also in advance of anticipated public health problems. HABISS is accessible through CDC’s Rapid Data Collector and is limited to individuals who have specifically requested and obtained digital certificates for security purposes. Data contributors can choose to enter, edit, and save data for subsequent sessions. Users may also choose to export data to Access, Excel, or XML. HABISS requires users to input several key indicators (e.g. dates, agency contact info, state codes, route of exposure, patient’s chief complaint, etc). If data is available, HABISS also prompts users to report the following data elements for a suspected human illness report: 1) Point of contact with the system, 2) Identifying information for the case, 3) Case demographics, 4) Environmental information, 5) Exposure information, 6) Signs and symptoms, 7) Medical Review (including laboratory analysis), 8) Case assessment and follow-up. MERGE (ssys58:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS58',`name`:'HIV Incidence Surveillance',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'HIV incidence is defined as the rate of new HIV infections over a defined period of time. HIV incidence can be used to appropriately target prevention resources to those most vulnerable to HIV transmission, identify masked or missed sub-epidemics, closely monitor for the emergence of new sub-epidemics of HIV in the general population, and measure the impact of HIV prevention programs. Several approaches have been used for measuring HIV incidence, yet each presents specific challenges. These main approaches include direct measurement in cohort studies, inference from HIV prevalence measurements in cross-sectional surveys using mathematical models, and a laboratory-based approach using tests for recent infection (TRI) in cross-sectional surveys. TRIs can be used to estimate national HIV-1 incidence in general populations in resource-constrained settings by applying the assay to specimens derived from national population based surveys with HIV testing (e.g. Demographic Health Surveys + and AIDS Indicator Surveys). Temporal trends in national HIV-1 incidence estimates can be subsequently assessed in countries that apply the assay in two or more consecutive rounds of national population based surveys. Temporal trends in HIV-1 incidence among target populations can also be tracked by applying the TRI to populations with three or more rounds of HIV sentinel surveillance. Finally, impact of PEPFAR supported HIV prevention programming can be measured using the TRI assay, through application of the assay to the targeted population at various cross-sectional points in time, including pre and post prevention programming.',`webResource`:'https://www.pepfar.net/C7/C8/HIV%20Incidence/default.aspx',`operationalStatus`:'Partially Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1985',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'International Partners',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys58;

MERGE (ssys63:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS63',`name`:'Influenza Hospitalization Surveillance Network',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'FluServ-NET',`purpose`:'The Epidemiology and Prevention Branch (EPB) in the Influenza Division at CDC collects, compiles and analyzes information on influenza activity in the United States and produces FluView, a weekly report from October through mid-May. The FluSurv-NET), one of many of the surveillance systems used by EPB, conducts surveillance for population-based, laboratory-confirmed influenza related hospitalizations in children (persons less than 18 years) and adults. Medical chart abstraction occurs for each hospitalized case meeting the surveillance case definition.   The FluSurv-NET covers over 80 counties in the 10 Emerging Infections Program (EIP) states (CA, CO, CT, GA, MD, MN, NM, NY, OR, TN) and additional Influenza Hospitalization Surveillance Project (IHSP) states.   The IHSP began during the 2009-2010 season to enhance surveillance during the 2009 H1N1 pandemic.  IHSP sites included IA, ID, MI, OK and SD during 2009-2010 season; ID, MI, OH, OK, RI, and UT during the 2010-2011 season; MI, OH, RI, and UT during the 2011-2012 season; and IA, MI, OH, RI, and UT during the 2012-2013 season. Data collected through this platform is used to monitor influenza disease severity and estimate influenza disease burden. Dissemination of health-related data collected through FluSurv-NET is disseminated in FluView, with periodic updates on influenza-associated hospitalization rates by age group. Incidence rates are calculated using the National Center for Health Statistics’ (NCHS) population estimates for the counties included in the surveillance catchment area.  The rates provided are likely to be a vast underestimate of the actual number of influenza-related hospitalizations. First, the FluSurv-NET is not nationally representative, and second, influenza-related hospitalizations can be missed, either because testing is not performed, or because cases may be attributed to other causes of pneumonia or other common influenza-related complications.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2003',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'State / Territorial Health Departments, Schools / Universities',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys63;

MERGE (ssys65:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS65',`name`:'Internally Displaced Persons Surveillance System - Haiti',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'IDPSS-Haiti',`purpose`:'On January 12, 2010, a 7.0-magnitude earthquake in Haiti disrupted infrastructure and displaced approximately 2 million persons, causing increased risk for communicable diseases from overcrowding and poor living conditions. Hundreds of nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) established health-care clinics in camps of internally displaced persons (IDPs). To monitor conditions of outbreak potential identified at NGO camp clinics, on February 18, the Haiti Ministry of Public Health and Population (MSPP), the Pan-American Health Organization (PAHO), and CDC implemented the IDP Surveillance System (IDPSS). The Inter-Agency Standing Committee (IASC) \"cluster approach\" was used to coordinate the Haiti humanitarian response. One of 11 clusters, the Global Health Cluster (GHC), builds global capacity, whereas the country-level cluster (in this case, the Haitian Health Cluster [HHC], led by PAHO) responds locally. During the Haiti response, HHC engaged NGOs serving large camps, established IDPSS, followed trends of reportable conditions, undertook epidemiologic and laboratory investigations, and fostered implementation of control measures. This report describes the design and implementation of IDPSS in the post-earthquake period. The primary challenges to implementing IDPSS were communication difficulties with an ever-changing group of NGO partners and limitations to the utility of IDPSS data because of lack of reliable camp population denominator estimates. The IDPSS experience reinforces the need to improve local communication and coordination strategies. Improving future humanitarian response requires advance development and distribution of easily adaptable standard surveillance tools, development of an interdisciplinary strategy for an early and reliable population census, and development of communication strategies using locally available Internet and cellular networks.',`webResource`:'Activity website not reported',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2010',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'International Partners',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys65;

Birth facility policies and practices that create a supportive environment for breastfeeding begin prenatally and continue after discharge. MERGE (ssys74:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS74',`name`:'Medical Electronic Request and Information System',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'MERIS supports both the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention’s (CDC) mission of health protection and the Division of Strategic National Stockpile (DSNS) mission to support partners and provide the right resources at the right time to secure the nation\'s health. MERIS will facilitate the request, management, distribution and follow up of critical medications targeted for use in hospitalized patients. Medical countermeasures (MCMs) envisioned to be distributed via MERIS may have limited or no commercial availability, and qualifiers are subject to specific uses under FDA-regulated mechanisms (Investigational New Drug Protocols, Emergency Use Authorizations, approvals). The system will use specific, rules, and limitations based on clinical, regulatory and logistical characteristics applicable to each MCM.  For example, there will be varying clinical eligibility criteria, dosing adjustments, delivery timeframes, and follow-up requirements defined for each specific MCM. The system will also be designed to scale in response to variable event levels ranging from small scale emergencies (e.g., single patient requiring product in one hospital in the country) to scenarios of larger scale mass causality incidence (e.g., numerous patients requiring product in multiple hospitals in the country). The solution created by the MERIS project will enable CDC to efficiently take the actions necessary to protect the public during health events that require specific DSNS critical medical countermeasures. Once fully enabled, MERIS will also provide federal, state, and local officials with timely information to manage public health response efforts requiring the distribution and use of specific SNS medical countermeasures. MERIS will provide critical care facilities nationwide with the ability to request SNS medical countermeasures electronically while providing the CDC with visibility into this activity from the request of a medical countermeasure through a confirmation of delivery and post-delivery follow-up on use-related data.',`webResource`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Under Development, but not yet Operational',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2013',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Healthcare Providers',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys74;

For this study, which was conducted in Atlanta during 1984-1990, investigators devised methods for determining the prevalence of intellectual disability, cerebral palsy, legal blindness, hearing loss, and epilepsy among children 10 years of age. Children who had these conditions were identified by searching record systems of sources that were likely to contain information relating to the evaluation or treatment of children with developmental disabilities (e.g., schools, hospitals, and state programs for persons who have developmental disabilities). The majority of the children were identified through special education departments within the Atlanta area public school systems. The success of this study prompted CDC to establish the Metropolitan Atlanta Developmental Disabilities Surveillance Program (MADDSP) in 1991, an ongoing system for monitoring the occurrence of selected developmental disabilities. MADDSP is located at CDC in the Developmental Disabilities Branch within the National Center on Birth Defects and Developmental Disabilities. The two principal objectives of MADDSP are to a) provide regular and systematic monitoring of the prevalence of selected developmental disabilities according to various demographic characteristics of children and their mothers and b) provide a framework for initiating special studies of children who have the selected developmental disabilities by establishing a population-based case series of such children. MERGE (ssys81:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS81',`name`:'Molecular Subtyping Network for Foodborne Disease Surveillance',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'PulseNet consists of a national network of public health laboratories that perform DNA fingerprinting on food-borne bacteria. The network permits rapid comparisons of these fingerprint patterns through an electronic database at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The DNA fingerprinting method is called pulsed-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE). PulseNet participants use a standardized protocol. They have the capability to exchange information electronically, allowing laboratories and epidemiologists in different states to rapidly compare DNA fingerprints of submitted strains with those in the PulseNet Database. Throughout the world, biomonitoring has become the standard for assessing people\'s exposure to toxic substances as well as for responding to serious environmental public health problems. Rather than estimating how much of a substance gets into people from measured environmental concentrations, our scientists have taken out the guesswork by measuring levels of chemicals that actually are in people\'s bodies. And they do so with precision, speed, and pinpoint accuracy, measuring many chemicals in a very small amount—often a teaspoon or less—of blood or urine. NBP currently measures more than 450 environmental chemicals and nutritional indicators in people. NHSN is managed by the Division of Healthcare Quality Promotion (DHQP) at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). NHSN assists DHQP in fulfilling its mission to: Protect patients, protect healthcare personnel, and promote safety, quality, and value in the healthcare delivery system by providing national leadership for measuring, validating, interpreting, and responding to data relevant to healthcare outcomes, healthcare-associated infections/antimicrobial resistance, related adverse events, and medical errors among patients and healthcare personnel. NHSN began as a voluntary surveillance system in 2005. However, since its launch that year, NHSN increasingly has served as the operational system for compliance with mandatory healthcare-associated infection (HAI) reporting requirements established by states. By 2010, 21 states had opted to use NHSN as the operational system for mandatory reporting by healthcare facilities in their jurisdictions, and additional states are expected to follow with similar use of NHSN for mandatory reporting purposes. In addition, the Center for Medicare and Medicaid (CMS) will require Medicare-eligible acute care hospitals to report HAI data to CMS via NHSN beginning with hospital discharges occurring January 1, 2011 as part of the Inpatient Prospective Payment System (IPPS) quality data reporting program. Further, federal legislative proposals could establish mandatory reporting of HAI data on the federal level. The data is used for epidemiologic analyses of disease activity in certain periods or locations by Dengue Branch scientists. Sample results are reported to the patients’ health care provider. Summary data of reported suspected cases and laboratory confirmed dengue cases is disseminated to stakeholders in Puerto Rico, for example the Puerto Rico Department of Health, and in the continental US. PRAMS collects state-specific, population-based data on maternal attitudes and experiences before, during, and shortly after pregnancy. PRAMS was initiated in 1987 because infant mortality rates were no longer declining as rapidly as they had in prior years. In addition, the incidence of low birth weight infants had changed little in the previous 20 years. Research has indicated that maternal behaviors during pregnancy may influence infant birth weight and mortality rates. The goal of the PRAMS project is to improve the health of mothers and infants by reducing adverse outcomes such as low birth weight, infant mortality and morbidity, and maternal morbidity. PRAMS provides state-specific data for planning and assessing health programs and for describing maternal experiences that may contribute to maternal and infant health. PRAMS provides data for state health officials to use to improve the health of mothers and infants. PRAMS allows CDC and the states to monitor changes in maternal and child health indicators (e.g., unintended pregnancy, prenatal care, breast-feeding, smoking, drinking, infant health). PRAMS enhances information from birth certificates used to plan and review state maternal and infant health programs. The PRAMS sample is chosen from all women who had a live birth recently, so findings can be applied to the state\'s entire population of women who have recently delivered a live-born infant. MERGE (ssys133:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS133',`name`:'Public Health Genomics Surveillance - Coordination Activity',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'Assessing the public’s awareness and use of genomic tests and family health history through population-based surveys provides important baseline data, and helps monitors progress toward implementing evidence-based recommendations, including those underlying Healthy People 2020 objectives. Additionally, it contributes to the knowledge base that supports the development and dissemination of appropriate public health messages and educational materials for the general public and health care providers, as well as informing federal and state policy. In 2012, the CDC Office of Public Health Genomics developed a three-tiered framework for classifying genomic tests and family health history based on the availability of scientific evidence and evidence-based recommendations supporting their use. Tier 1 genomic applications are recommended for clinical use by evidence-based panels, based on systematic review of evidence of validity and utility. Tier 2 applications may be useful for informed decision making in clinical practice, based on demonstrated validity, and promising utility.  Tier 3 applications are not ready for clinical use, due to validity or utility not demonstrated, or systematic assessment finding harms outweigh benefits. States are assessing awareness and use of specific Tier 1, 2 and 3 genomic applications using state-added questions in the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS). Ethical, legal and social issues:  The potential for genetic discrimination is a concern relevant to the increased availability of genetic information associated with the increased use of genetic tests in clinical practice and in the direct-to-consumer market.  The Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act (GINA) was signed into law in 2008. While GINA is designed to protect against discrimination in health insurance coverage and employment, it does not address other areas where discrimination is possible, such as in life, disability and long-term care insurance. More information is needed on the extent that the general public is aware of protections offered under GINA, and is concerned about the potential for genetic discrimination, since these may prove to be significant factors affecting the uptake of genetic testing. Four questions were added to BRFSS in Michigan, Oregon, Ohio, and Connecticut to collect this information.',`webResource`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2008',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'Members Of General Public',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Members Of General Public',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'State / Territorial Health Departments',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys133;

MERGE (ssys143:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS143',`name`:'Search for Diabetes in Youth',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'Search',`purpose`:'In response to a growing public health concern, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the National Institutes of Health (NIH) are funding a 5-year, multicenter study, SEARCH for Diabetes in Youth, to examine the current status of diabetes among children and adolescents in the United States. The primary goals of SEARCH are 1) to develop a uniform classification of types of childhood diabetes (no \"gold standard\" definitions of types now exist) 2) to estimate the number of new (incidence) and existing (prevalence) childhood diabetes cases by type, age of the child, sex, and racial or ethnic group 3) to describe the clinical characteristics of different types of diabetes in youth and how they evolved 4) to describe the complications of diabetes in children and adolescents 5) to describe the quality of life of children and adolescents with diabetes. Six U.S. sites collaborate with CDC and NIH on SEARCH. The youth population being studied is provided by the six SEARCH sites and involves more than 5 million, or 6 percent, of all American children aged 0 to 19 years. This will be the largest and most racially and geographically diverse study group ever involved in a youth diabetes study. During the 5-year study period, the SEARCH sites will examine more than 6,000 existing cases of pediatric diabetes and about 800 new cases each year. Data collection began in 2002. With data provided by the SEARCH study, scientists can follow current cases of childhood diabetes to monitor any changes that occur in the type, characteristics, and outcomes of specific cases. The data collection of childhood diabetes cases will provide valuable information to researchers and health care providers in developing appropriate care and treatment protocols that will reduce the likelihood of complications and lessen the burden of diabetes in the daily lives of children and adolescents with diabetes.',`webResource`:'http://www.searchfordiabetes.org/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2001',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'Cincinnati, Seattle, Southern California',`dataProviders-Manual`:'Schools / Universities',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys143;

MERGE (ssys147:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS147',`name`:'State Injury Indicators',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'SII',`purpose`:'The State Injury Indicators utilize data drawn from state vital statistics records, state hospital discharge data (HDD), state emergency department (ED) data, the National Center for Health Statistics’ National Vital Statistics System (NVSS), the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality’s Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project (HCUP), Nationwide Inpatient Sample (NIS) and Nationwide Emergency Department Sample (NEDS), the Youth Risk Behavior Survey (YRBS), the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS), and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration’s Fatality Analysis Reporting System (FARS). The methods used have been developed using a consensus building process working group with representatives from the Safe States Alliance, the Council of State and Territorial Epidemiologists (CSTE), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and its National Center for Injury Prevention and Control (NCIPC), and the Society for Advancement of Violence and Injury Research (SAVIR). Methods are fully delineated in the annual State Injury Indicators: Instructions for Preparing Data manuals. In brief, injury hospitalization and emergency department cases are identified from state-based HDD  and ED data using the principal diagnosis (or first-listed ICD-9-CM diagnosis code) with other selective factors. Injury deaths are identified from vital statistics data using the ICD-10 underlying-cause-of-death codes. All multiple-cause-of-death fields are searched for the fatal TBI indicator. For comparison purposes, national rates for the fatality indicators are generated by using the NVSS. National rates for the hospitalization and emergency department visit indicators are generated using the HCUP, NIS, and NEDS.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/injury/stateprograms/indicators.html',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2004',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys147;

MACDP is an active surveillance system whereby trained staff regularly visit hospitals and clinics throughout metropolitan Atlanta. By using multiple sources for ascertainment, it is more likely that all births affected by a birth defect will be identified. This same system can potentially be used to identify all pregnancies resulting in a stillbirth. MACDP has begun active surveillance of all stillbirths in the 5 central counties of Atlanta. The stillbirth surveillance pilot project will assess whether MACDP can be expanded to include data on all stillbirths. Active surveillance of stillbirths should provide better estimates on its occurrence in the five counties, as well as improve the quality of the information gathered. Information on stillbirths with birth defects is already collected by MACDP. This pilot project involves making the necessary changes so that more information can be collected about all stillbirths, both with and without identifiable birth defects. About half of these are called Sudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS).The SUID CR is a multi-state surveillance system developed to more accurately monitor SUID trends. The purpose of SUID case registry is to collect comprehensive and standardized information about the circumstances and events associated with SUID case; and to improve the quality of SUID data collection systems by developing and maintaining an active surveillance system of all SUID. The SUID Case Registry collects information (including reports from death scene investigations, autopsy, medical and social service records, death and birth certificates) concerning important environmental and physiologic characteristics associated with SUID, as well as information about the completeness of death scene investigations and autopsies that were conducted. The registry builds upon current efforts by the HRSA’s MCHB National Center for Child Death Review (CDR) and local and state child death review teams. The national trichinellosis surveillance system is a passive system that relies on existing resources at the local, state, and federal levels. Cases are diagnosed based on clinical history with laboratory confirmation of Trichinella infection. Cases are reported weekly to CDC through the National Electronic Telecommunications System for Surveillance (NETSS). Detailed data regarding signs and symptoms, diagnostic tests, and food consumption are gathered by using a supplementary standardized surveillance form and are reported to CDC by fax or mail. This information is compared with NETSS data several times a year by CDC staff. Discrepancies are reviewed with the state health departments. MERGE (ssys154:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS154',`name`:'Survey of Coal Mine Safety Interventions',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'Although the NIOSH Office of Mine Safety and Health Research widely disseminates and publicizes research results, recommendations, techniques and products, the agency has limited knowledge about the extent to which their innovations in mine safety and health have been implemented by individual mine operators. This is particularly true of methods and practices that are not mandated by formal regulations. The overarching goal of Survey of Coal Mine Safety Interventions is to gather data from working coal mines on the adoption and implementation of OMSHR practices to mitigate safety and occupational hazards (e.g., explosions, falls of ground). The information from this survey will be used by OMSHR to evaluate the implementation of safety and health interventions (including best practices and barriers to implementation) in areas such as respirable coal dust control, explosion prevention, roof support, and emergency response planning and training. Survey results will provide OMSHR with knowledge about which recommended practices, tools and methods have been most widely embraced by the mining industry, which have not been adopted, and why. MERGE (ssys159:`SurveillanceSystem`{`id`:'SS159',`name`:'US Outpatient Influenza-Like Illness Surveillance Network',`fullName`:'',`shortName`:'ILINet',`purpose`:'The Outpatient Influenza-like Illness Surveillance Network (ILINet) consists of about 3,400 healthcare providers in 50 states reporting approximately 25 million patient visits each year. Each week, approximately 2,000 outpatient care sites around the country report data to CDC on the total number of patients seen and the number of those patients with influenza-like illness (ILI) by age group. For this system, ILI is defined as fever (temperature of 100°F [37.8°C] or greater) and a cough and/or a sore throat in the absence of a KNOWN cause other than influenza. Sites with electronic records use an equivalent definition as determined by the state public health authorities. The percentage of patient visits to healthcare providers for ILI reported each week is weighted on the basis of state population. This percentage is compared each week with the annually calculated national baseline. The baseline is the mean percentage of patient visits for ILI during non-influenza weeks for the previous three seasons plus two standard deviations. Due to wide variability in regional level data, it is not appropriate to apply the national baseline to regional data, therefore, region specific baselines are calculated.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/flu',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1982',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'Healthcare Providers',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Healthcare Providers, Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Local Health Departments, Members Of General Public, State / Territorial Health Departments',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return ssys159;

Protecting, promoting, and supporting breastfeeding, with its many known benefits for infants, children, and mothers, is a key strategy toward this goal. The Breastfeeding Report Card shows how breastfeeding is being protected, promoted, and supported in each state using five \"outcome\" and six \"process\" indicators. This allows you to make comparisons across states and indicators and work to increase breastfeeding nationwide. The five outcome indicators are derived from the breastfeeding goals outlined in Healthy People 2010, a description of the nation\'s health priorities. They profile the extent to which infants in a state are breastfed. The nine process indicators measure elements of breastfeeding-friendly communities. Each indicator is measured in every state, allowing easy state-by-state comparisons. MERGE (tool10:`Tool`{`id`:'TL10',`name`:'Early Aberration Reporting System',`fullName`:'Early Aberration Reporting System',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'EARS is a cost-free to end user SAS-based and Excel-based (two versions are available) analysis and reporting software tool allowing public health departments to monitor surveillance data available to them using aberration detection methods. The goal of the tool is to assist public health professionals in the early identification and monitoring of outbreaks of disease, as well as other public health and medical events, with emphasis on outbreaks that may indicate intentional releases of biological agents. The EARS tool facilitates creation of user-identified event/syndrome categories by which data are aggregated. Aberration detection algorithms then assess whether observed counts or rates for a particular category are higher than usual. The EARS tool reports are interactive, allowing users to \"drill down\" into their raw data to investigate aberrations, and they can also automatically populate websites for sharing. It is designed to run on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis and can be set up to run automatically.',`webResource`:'http://www.emergency.cdc.gov/surveillance/ears/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return tool10;

MERGE (tool16:`Tool`{`id`:'TL16',`name`:'Exposure Investigation',`fullName`:'Exposure Investigation',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'An exposure investigation is one approach ATSDR uses to develop better characterization of past, current, and possible future human exposures to hazardous substances in the environment and to evaluate existing and possible health effects related to those exposures more thoroughly. There are three main ways information is gathered during an exposure investigation: Bio-medical testing (for example, urine or blood samples) is an important piece of information gathered and evaluated during an ATSDR exposure investigation. Bio-medical samples can show current (and sometimes past) exposure to a contaminant. Environmental testing (for contamination of soil, water, or air) is also an important piece of information gathered and evaluated during an exposure investigation. ATSDR investigators focus environmental testing on where people live, spend time and play, or might come in contact with contaminants under investigation. Our branch also has expertise in exposure dose reconstruction. Exposure-dose reconstruction analyses use environmental sampling information and computer models to estimate the contaminant levels that people may have been exposed to in the past or may be exposed to in the future. We can use these models to draw various conclusions. For example, how long and at what levels a drinking water well has been contaminated. We can then use the information to evaluate how a person\'s health might be affected.',`webResource`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Retired',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return tool16;

Its purpose is to ensure the quality and availability of LRN data and decrease the time needed to detect and respond to public health threats. The LRN is a coordinated network of public health and other laboratories for which CDC provides standard assays and protocols for testing biological and chemical terrorism agents. LRN Results Messenger (LRN RM) is a software solution created to provide LRN labs with the immediate ability to manage and share standard laboratory data. LRN RM is currently installed over 160 LRN laboratories, including 100% of the LRN’s public health labs. LRN RM provides basic laboratory data management, including the ability to enter and share sample and results data. The application enables labs to submit and respond to electronic test requests from other LRN labs, which supports the mutual assistance functionality of the LRN. The application embodies PHIN requirements and utilizes CDC’s Secure Data Network and PHIN Messaging System infrastructure. LRN Results Viewer is deployed within the CDC and provides a database to store LRN results and the ability to query and view those results. The Laboratory Information Management System Integration (LIMSi) activity is a parallel effort to LRN RM. It represents the next generation of the incremental approach to data exchange for the LRN. Its purpose is to enable laboratories to fulfill data exchange needs for the LRN using their own systems by implementing data standards and infrastructure to support Health Level 7 (HL7) messaging. LIMSi  has facilitated collaborative efforts between CDC and public health laboratory subject matter experts to refine system requirements needed to configure laboratory information management systems (LIMS) to manage LRN testing. Registry Plus currently includes ten applications, plus various utility programs: Abstract Plus, Web Plus, eMaRC Plus, Data File Mapper Plus, Prep Plus, Central Registry System (CRS) Plus, including Tumor Linkage and Consolidation (TLC) Plus, Link Plus, Registry Plus Online Help, EditWriter, and GenEDITS Plus. The NPCR Registry Plus suite of applications offers central cancer registries reporting solutions for all levels of data reporting sources. The online abstracting capability of Web Plus is suitable for reporting from physicians’ offices and other low-volume reporting sources, while the file upload feature can be used for electronic submission of data from all other reporting sources (often along with the offline abstraction capability of Abstract Plus). Web Plus also supports death certificate and pathology lab follow-back efforts.  eMaRC Plus can be used to receive and map electronic pathology lab files in HL7 format to NAACCR abstracts that can be processed into the central registry. Functionality to map Electronic Heath Records received in in CDA format is also currently being added to the program. The file mapping functions of the eMaRC Plus and Data File Mapper Plus tools can be used to generate follow-back files for loading into Web Plus, as well as to map files received by central registries in formats other than NAACCR-formatted files. Once received, the data may be cleaned and edited with Prep Plus, and then consolidated and maintained using CRS Plus. In addition, Link Plus provides the capability to detect duplicates within a cancer registry or to link files of cancer registry data to external files.',`webResource`:'http://www.cdc.gov/cancer/npcr/tools/registryplus/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return tool33;

From the beginning, the 2ndHealth version of the Worker Health Chartbook was intended to permit access and dissemination of contents to the maximum extent possible. In addition to a print version, NIOSH developed a website based on the content of the 2nd Chartbook. Our intent was to increase both access and availability of the content to the user community. The web version permits visitors to copy text, download the actual charts (*.gif format) and tables, link to external sources based on the extensively documented tables and references, and appendices. The Worker Health eChartbook (hereafter eChartbook) is a continuation of these previous efforts. Begun in late 2005, a small cadre of staff has been developing the new Worker Health eChartbook primarily as a web-based occupational safety and health statistics resources. Many of the features associated with the 2nd Worker Health Chartbook (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2004-146/) are found here, with the exception of a print document. The current contents include more than 18,000 figures and tables describing the magnitude, distribution, and trends of the Nation\'s occupational injuries, illnesses, and fatalities. In 2011 we plan to expand the resource to include more extensive listing of morbidity and mortality data (chapter 4), state-specific content, as well as general population health status and risk. Also, work is proceeding to develop and include content economics and quality of work life. The eChartbook will continue to grow and develop to reflect the growing data and information needs of the NIOSH Program Portfolio (see http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/programs/). CPONDER contains PRAMS data from 2000 through 2006 for state/year combinations that achieve at least a 70% response rate. CPONDER contains 2007 and 2008 data for PRAMS state/year combinations that achieve at least a 65% response rate. As additional years of data are weighted, they will be added to the system. The system indexes 54 variables by topic for selection as the outcome variable in the analyses. In addition, there are 12 control variables for use in breaking out or stratifying the requested analysis— only one break-out variable at a time may be specified. PRAMS collects state-specific, population-based data on maternal attitudes and experiences before, during, and shortly after pregnancy. PRAMS was initiated in 1987 because infant mortality rates were no longer declining as rapidly as they had in prior years. In addition, the incidence of low birth weight infants had changed little in the previous 20 years. Research has indicated that maternal behaviors during pregnancy may influence infant birth weight and mortality rates. The goal of the PRAMS project is to improve the health of mothers and infants by reducing adverse outcomes such as low birth weight, infant mortality and morbidity, and maternal morbidity. PRAMS provides state-specific data for planning and assessing health programs and for describing maternal experiences that may contribute to maternal and infant health. PONDER, a web-based query system located on the Inside PRAMS website that is available to CDC and state project staff. PONDER includes weighted data from the PRAMS questionnaire and provides real-time prevalence estimates and robust standard errors through a user friendly, web-enabled, point and click interface. PONDER enables users to perform cross tabulations and generate basic descriptive statistics (e.g., means, weighted and raw counts). Cigarette smoking and exposure to tobacco smoke resulted in at least 443,000 premature deaths, approximately 5.1 million years of potential life lost (YPLL), and $96.8 billion in productivity losses annually in the United States (CDC, 2008). Since 1987, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has used the Smoking-Attributable Mortality, Morbidity, and Economic Costs (SAMMEC) application to estimate the disease impact of smoking for the nation, states, and large populations. The SAMMEC application has been used to estimate smoking-attributable mortality (SAM), YPLL, direct medical expenditures, and productivity losses. However, the primary focus of SAMMEC has been to measure the deaths and years of life lost due to smoking. These estimates were based on an attributable-fraction methodology that applies current information on cigarette smoking prevalence to scientific data on the relative risk of death from diseases shown to be caused by smoking. Estimates are necessary in the absence of adequate information on death certificates about the smoking history of individuals.',`webResource`:'http://apps.nccd.cdc.gov/sammec/index.asp',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'NULL',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return tool47;

MERGE (reg4:`Registry`{`id`:'RG4',`name`:'International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research',`fullName`:'International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research',`shortName`:'',`registryType`:'',`purpose`:'The International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research (ICBDSR, or Clearinghouse in short) is a voluntary nonprofit International Organization affiliated with WHO. The Organization brings together birth defect surveillance and research programs from around the world with the aim of investigating and preventing birth defects and lessening the impact of their consequences. The Organization was first established in 1974, at a meeting in Helsinki, Finland, where representatives of malformation registries in ten countries were present. It was named the International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Monitoring Systems (ICBDMS) and member programs were actively engaged in the systematic collection and analysis of data for the comprehensive monitoring of congenital malformations. In 2003/4, a strategic planning group was set up with the aim of suggesting new strategic goals for the Organization. These suggestions were approved at the Clearinghouse Annual Meeting in Japan, 2004 and the Organization under the current name of International Clearinghouse for Birth Defects Surveillance and Research (ICBDSR), was officially established. It now has 44 member programs worldwide. The mission of the International Clearinghouse of Birth Defects Surveillance and Research is to conduct worldwide surveillance and research into the occurrence and possible causes of Birth Defects with the aim of preventing them and decreasing their consequences. The strategic priority of the Clearinghouse is to conduct worldwide surveillance and to exchange data about birth defects. The scope of the Clearinghouse includes fetal and childhood conditions of prenatal cause. Participating surveillance programs will carry out systematic data collection and use the data for public health action. Public health action includes comparing prevalence rates, advocacy, policy development, conducting epidemiological studies of causes and consequences of birth defects, assessing preventive and therapeutic interventions, and interacting with the public, research institutions and relevant government agencies.',`webResource`:'http://www.icbdsr.org',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'1974',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'5 counties of metropolitan Atlanta: Clayton, Cobb, Dekalb, Fulton, and Gwinett',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers, State / Territorial Health Departments',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'Federal Government Agencies, International Partners, Healthcare Providers, Members Of General Public, State / Territorial Health Departments, Schools / Universities',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return reg4;

It collects data on the occurrence of cancer; the type, extent, and location of the cancer; and the type of initial treatment. NPCR supports central cancer registries in 45 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Pacific Island Jurisdictions. These data represent 96% of the U.S. population. In each U.S. state, DC, and territory, local and regional cancer data are reported to central cancer registries about all new diagnoses of cancer from patient records at such medical facilities as hospitals, physicians\'offices, therapeutic radiation facilities, freestanding surgical centers, and pathology laboratories. These data are submitted annually in November to CDC’s NPCR. Data collected by local cancer registries enable public health professionals to understand and address the cancer burden more effectively.
