MERGE (reg10:`Registry`{`id`:'RG10',`name`:'National Select Agent Registry',`fullName`:'National Select Agent Registry',`shortName`:'',`registryType`:'',`purpose`:'The 2002 Bioterrorism Preparedness & Response Act requires entities to register with the U.S. Department of Health & Human Services (HHS) or Agriculture (USDA) if they possess, use, or transfer Select Biological Agents (SA) or Toxins that could pose a severe threat to public health and safety, animal/plant health, or animal/plant products. The 2002 Act (Public Law 107-188) requires maintenance of a national database of entities that are registered for possession of SA & toxins, laboratory compliance with national safety guidelines, security measures including controlled access to SA & toxins, security screening of entities and personnel, and criminal/civil penalties for inappropriate use of SA/toxins. NSAR is a joint CDC & USDA Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) program designed to control, protect, store & oversee the use, possession & transfer of SA & toxins which resulted from an OMB directive for the USDA and CDC to collaborate. NSAR maintains information regarding an entity’s SA registration, lists SA/toxins they possess, records individual access & laboratory inspection information, and lists where SA work is conducted. Access & accurate processing of SA data via the NSAR system is intended to enable agencies to increase their ability to enforce and prevent the spread of infectious diseases and illnesses. Individuals desiring to conduct research related activities are screened and approved by Department of Justice\'s Criminal Justice Information Services. NSAR supports PMA E-Gov by minimizing data collection/entry redundancy, improving information sharing, and is expected to reduce the entities reporting burden when forms are submitted electronically. As a result of a comprehensive Operational Assessment, the CDC, APHIS and other key stakeholders have determined that the NSAR investment, in its current form, does not have the functionality and technical capabilities necessary to support the business and strategic goals of the organization. Consequently, it has been determined that continuing to invest funds in the development, modernization & enhancement of NSAR is no longer justifiable. The funding section of this investment demonstrates that Planning & Acquisition activities for the current investment will reduce and begin to cease in FY10. The Initiation Phase as defined by the HHS Enterprise Performance Life Cycle Framework for a new investment (the replacement for NSAR) will begin in FY10.',`webResource`:'http://www.selectagents.gov/',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`startDate`:'',`startDateGeneration`:'2003',`surveillanceType`:'',`surveillanceDomain`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Schools / Universities, Veterinarians',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'Federal Government Agencies, Healthcare Providers, Public Laboratories, Private Laboratories , Local Health Departments, State / Territorial Health Departments, Schools / Universities, Veterinarians',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`patientTrackingCapability`:'',`overallCapability`:'',`ageFormat`:'',`specialPopulations`:'',`applicationSolutionType`:'',`applicationPlatform`:'',`operatingSystemPlatform`:'',`databaseTechnology`:'',`dataPayloadFormat`:'',`dataPayloadTransmissionType`:'',`analysis,Visualization,AndReporting(AVR)Capability`:'',`reportFrequency`:'',`evaluationDate`:'',`evaluationDetails`:'',`fundingSource`:'',`fundingLevels`:'',`nationalBiosurveillanceStrategyMapping`:'',`city`:'',`state`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return reg10;

Since its inception in 2002, the registry has evolved into the largest post disaster follow-up in US history and is recognized as the primary source for epidemiological findings regarding the effects of 9-11 related exposures for both physical and mental health disease. Peer reviewed objective and scientifically valid data from the registry on the long term health burden of 9-11 has resulted in continued medical monitoring and treatment of 9-11 rescue/recovery workers, lower Manhattan residents, and children who were enrolled in schools in the vicinity of WTC. The registry has also been used by external researchers who have completed studies in such areas as building evacuation safety and procedures and biological basis for Post traumatic stress disorder. MERGE (colla2:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO2',`name`:'Biosurveillance Coordination Activity',`fullName`:'Biosurveillance Coordination Activity',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'In 2007, Homeland Security Presidential Directive 21 (HSPD-21) was issued in recognition of the emergence of significant health-related threats to the nation. HSPD-21 called for the development of a nationwide approach to biosurveillance in order to enhance the United States’ ability to detect and respond to those threats. HSPD-21 defines biosurveillance as— …the process of active data-gathering with appropriate analysis and interpretation of biosphere data that might relate to disease activity and threats to human or animal health—whether infectious, toxic, metabolic, or otherwise, and regardless or intentional or natural origin—in order to achieve early warning of health threats, early detection of health events, and overall situational awareness of disease activity. The Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) was charged with the responsibility of enhancing biosurveillance for human health and delegated this responsibility to CDC. In 2008, CDC established the Biosurveillance Coordination unit (BC) to oversee the necessary activities to address these mandates. With input from federal, state, local, tribal, and private stakeholders, the BC unit coordinated the release of the first draft version of the National Biosurveillance Strategy for Human Health (NBSHH) in December 2008. The NBSHH established priorities for the nation’s next-generation biosurveillance capability to provide timely, comprehensive, and accessible information to strengthen public health practice, provide value to clinicians, and build upon current systems and resources. Version 2 of the National Biosurveillance Strategy for Human Health (NBSHH) was extensively revised and expanded to include additional information. It was released in February 2010.',`operationStartDate`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`collaborativeParticipants`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return colla2;

A sensitive and specific IgM antibody assay was developed to assist in the laboratory confirmation of suspected measles cases. In addition, viral isolates were collected for genetic analysis and characterization. The information from the characterization of viruses analyzed during the 1989-1991 resurgence of measles and the ongoing viral surveillance throughout the 1990s was important data that helped to document the elimination of endemic transmission of measles in the United States. Responsibility for rubella and mumps viruses was transferred to the Measles Virus Section in 1997-1998. MERGE (colla19:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO19',`name`:'Pediatric HIV Surveillance',`fullName`:'Pediatric HIV Surveillance',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'Pediatric HIV surveillance has been lacking in resource-constrained international settings, hindering planning and implementation of prevention, care and treatment programs. Our program has been involved in providing guidance to different countries on conducting pediatric HIV surveillance activities to contribute to their understanding of the magnitude of the epidemic among children, thereby guiding policy and program decision-making. Thus far, we have been involved in developing and writing publications and presentations advocating for pediatric HIV surveillance, describing pediatric HIV surveillance approaches, and providing strategies for designing systems to track pediatric HIV. Currently, we recommend multiple approaches depending on the epidemic context and resource availability of each country, including HIV case reporting, population-based surveys with HIV testing of children, immunization clinic surveys, mortality surveillance, and special surveys. MERGE (colla22:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO22',`name`:'Public Health Information Network',`fullName`:'Public Health Information Network',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'The Public Health Information Network (PHIN) is a national initiative to increase the capacity of public health agencies to electronically exchange data and information across organizations and jurisdictions (e.g., clinical care to public health, public health to public health and public health to other federal agencies). To do so, PHIN promotes the use of standards and defines functional and technical requirements for public health information exchange. The mission of PHIN is to establish and support shared policies, standards, practices, and services that facilitate efficient public health information access, exchange, use, and collaboration among public health agencies and with their clinical and other partners. The vision of PHIN is an integrated healthcare and public health system using information effectively to advance population health and well-being. Programmatic activities for the PHIN initiative including strategic planning, administration, management, and operations reside in the Division of Informatics Practice, Policy, and Coordination (DIPPC) in CDC’s Public Health Surveillance and Informatics Program Office. The Public Health Surveillance and Informatics Program Office supports the PHIN initiative by developing and disseminating requirements, standards, specifications, and overall architecture for public health information exchange; monitoring the information exchange capabilities of state and local health agencies; developing methods to validate, test, and certify electronic messages; promoting the use of public health information exchange to improve emergency preparedness outcomes; communicating the value of public health information exchange to public health practice; working with CDC programs to establish governance for policies, standards, practices, and services, standardize the approach to system interoperability, ensure alignment with the Nationwide Health Information Network (NwHIN) and other federal initiatives; working with federal partners and other external stakeholders to ensure that the public health community is represented through a governance model, and support the interoperability of the public health segment of the federal health IT architecture.',`operationStartDate`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Fully Operational and Implemented',`collaborativeParticipants`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return colla22;

MERGE (colla24:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO24',`name`:'Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology',`fullName`:'Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology',`shortName`:'ROGUE',`purpose`:'The purpose of Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology (ROGUE) working group is to 1) Reduce the number of foodborne illnesses with unknown etiology and 2) Provide epidemiologic and laboratory assistance when possible. The Rapid Onset of Gastroenteritis with Unexplained Etiology (ROGUE) working group investigates foodborne diseases that may have a chemical etiology. Since the most common foodborne illnesses are due to biological organisms, these are much more commonly considered early in an outbreak. Recognition of chemical etiologies is often not made until later, and this hinders ultimate identification of responsible agents because of the timeliness with which samples must be collected. Better clues are needed to help clinicians and public health officials determine if a foodborne outbreak may have a chemical etiology. People that become ill from chemical contaminants in food may comment that the food had an unusual taste, smell or appearance. These organoleptic qualities can be important clues in identifying the types of agents that may have contaminated the food and caused illness, as well as helpful in identifying that a chemical induced foodborne illness may be occurring. Unfortunately, in the investigation of foodborne illness complaints, this type of information is seldom collected in a uniform manner.',`operationStartDate`:'NULL',`operationalStatus`:'Retired',`collaborativeParticipants`:'',`conditionsUnderSurveillance`:'',`geographicCoverageArea`:'',`dataProviders-Manual`:'',`dataProviders-Electronic`:'',`dataRecipients-Manual`:'',`dataRecipients-Electronic`:'',`contactName`:'',`contactEmail`:'',`contactPhone`:'',`Notes`:'',`lastUpdated`:'',`informationValidated`:''}) return colla24;

MERGE (colla28:`Collaborative`{`id`:'CO28',`name`:'WHO Collaborating Center for Rotavirus and the Agents of Viral Gastroenteritis',`fullName`:'WHO Collaborating Center for Rotavirus and the Agents of Viral Gastroenteritis',`shortName`:'',`purpose`:'CDC’s - Rotavirus Program serves as a World Health Organization (WHO) Collaborating Center for rotavirus and other viral agents of gastroenteritis. WHO designated the Rotavirus Program a Collaborating Center beginning in 1998 and redesignation occurs every five years. The primary role of the CDC Rotavirus Collaborating Center is to support the WHO Global Rotavirus Surveillance Network that collects data on rotavirus disease burden and strain prevalence as part of efforts to introduce rotavirus vaccines globally. Globally, rotavirus is the cause of about  450,000 diarrheal deaths every year,  almost all of which occur in  developing countries. In addition, many more children will get dehydrated and require medical intervention and hospitalization. Several vaccines against rotavirus have been, or are being, developed to reduce this burden. Since 2006, two live attenuated vaccines against rotavirus have been licensed in more than 100 countries around the world and are now recommended by WHO for global use. One component of efforts to introduce rotavirus vaccines globally is the derivation of global, regional and local disease burden and strain prevalence estimates to help make the case for vaccination and to support countries decisions about rotavirus vaccine introduction.. The CDC and WHO have developed a generic protocol for standardized surveillance of rotavirus disease burden and strain prevalence, and with support from the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization (GAVI) and in collaboration with CDC and country partners, WHO has recently developed a Global Rotavirus Surveillance Network made up of regional networks (about 60 countries) in the six WHO regions (Americas, Africa, European, Eastern Mediterranean, Southeast Asia and Western Pacific Regions) to collect current data.  The role of the CDC Rotavirus Program and its Collaborating Center is to provide the WHO with technical expertise and laboratory and epidemiologic support to aid in network activities. Another Rotavirus Collaborating Center from Melbourne, Australia and Rotavirus Reference Laboratories from the six WHO regions provide region-specific laboratory support. Terms of reference of the center: 1. To conduct evaluations of rotavirus vaccines in collaboration with the Department of Vaccines and Biologicals (V&B, WHO) and developing country investigators. 2. To conduct rotavirus disease and strain surveillance with support from the Childhood Vaccine Program, Program of Appropriate Technology in Health (PATH) of the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, and V&B, WHO 3. To serve as a vaccine evaluation training center for scientists for developing and developed countries. 4. To provide assistance in characterization and referencing of viral strains from WHO supported studies. 5. It is used by U.S. federal government agencies collecting occupational data, enabling comparison of occupations across data sets. It is designed to cover all occupations in which work is performed for pay or profit, reflecting the current occupational structure in the United States. The 2010 SOC includes 840 occupational types.[1]   Users of occupational data include government program managers, industrial and labor relations practitioners, students considering career training, job seekers, vocational training schools, and employers wishing to set salary scales or locate a new plant.   The SOC codes have a hierarchical format, so for example the code \"15-0000\" refers to occupations in the \"Computer and Mathematical Occupations\" category, and \"15-1130\" is a subset for \"Software Developers and Programmers.\" [2]   The SOC does not categorize industries or employers. There are orthogonal category systems for industries used with SOC data, most commonly NAICS.
